#### Ho-4: Knowing Your Rights as a Renter or Homeowner
*Strategy:* Assert + Decode
*See also:* L-1: Negotiating a Contract (for reading your lease or mortgage), C-3: Understanding Your Rights Where You Live (for rights that vary by jurisdiction), C-6: Advocating for Change (for changing the rules)
*My Man Jeeves:* _Housing law, one might observe, is the domain in which the greatest sums change hands with the least comprehension on one side of the transaction. The landlord retains a property management company that has filed the same lease in the same county for fifteen years. The HOA board has engaged an attorney on retainer who drafted the CC&Rs. The mortgage servicer employs a compliance department that knows precisely which fees are legal and which are merely customary. The individual on the other side of the table has the document they were given and a vague apprehension that some of it is not quite right. That apprehension is, in the general course of things, well founded. The law is specific, it varies by jurisdiction, and it almost invariably provides more rights than one supposes. The difficulty has never been the law itself. The difficulty is that nobody has explained it. One's Agent has read the law and is prepared to do so._
*The Spec:*

::: prompt
I have a question about my rights as a [renter / homeowner / HOA member].
My situation:
— Where I live: [city, state]
— My housing type: [apartment / house / condo / mobile home / HOA community]
— The issue: [describe — lease dispute, security deposit, HOA rule,
   property tax assessment, landlord not making repairs, noise complaint,
   accessibility need, pet restriction, utility billing, or "I just want
   to understand what rights I have"]
— What has happened so far: [if anything — notices sent, conversations
   had, complaints filed]
Please help me:
1. What are my specific rights in this situation under my
   state and local law?
2. What is the process for enforcing those rights — who do I
   contact, what do I file, what are the deadlines?
3. What are the most common mistakes people make in this
   situation that weaken their position?
4. If this involves a dispute: what is my strongest argument,
   and what documentation do I need?
Give me the most conservative, legally accurate answer.
I will verify with a tenant rights organization or attorney.

:::
*What to do with the Output:* Document everything in writing. If your landlord or HOA is violating your rights, your Agent can help you draft the letter — but send it by email or certified mail so there is a record. Many cities have free tenant rights hotlines and legal aid organizations; ask your Agent to find the one in your jurisdiction. The clock on most housing disputes starts running whether you know about the deadline or not.

::: tip
_"I just signed a lease I didn't fully understand. [Paste the section you're worried about.] What did I actually agree to, and is any of it unenforceable in [state]?"_ — The time to understand your lease is now, not when there is a dispute.

:::


::: fairness
Housing rights enforcement varies dramatically by race, income, and geography. Matthew Desmond's _Evicted_ (2016) documented how eviction functions less as a legal remedy of last resort than as an instrument of housing control, concentrated in Black and Latino neighborhoods even after controlling for income. The Eviction Lab at Princeton --- which tracks filings across 10 states and more than 30 cities --- recorded just over 1 million eviction cases in 2024, an average filing rate of 7.8% of renter households, with nine of its tracked cities filing above 10%.[^ho4-1] If your Agent's advice assumes a responsive landlord or a functional enforcement system, say so: _"My landlord ignores repair requests and I'm worried about retaliation if I push harder. What are my protections?"_

:::


::: also
Paste or upload your lease, HOA rules, or property tax assessment directly — file upload works in Claude, Gemini, ChatGPT, and Copilot. See [Appendix G](06-appendix-g-feature-table.xhtml).

:::


::: also
Active-duty servicemembers, National Guard and Reserve members on federal orders of 30+ days, and their dependents are covered by the Servicemembers Civil Relief Act ([50 U.S.C. §§ 3901--4043](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?path=/prelim@title50/chapter50&edition=prelim)). SCRA allows early lease termination on permanent-change-of-station or 90-day deployment orders (written notice plus a copy of the orders; the lease ends 30 days after the next rent due date), prohibits eviction from residential premises below a statutory rent ceiling (adjusted annually by the Secretary of Defense; $10,239.63 per month for 2025) without a court order, and caps interest on pre-service debts --- mortgages, credit cards, auto loans --- at 6% with written notice to the creditor. Ask your Agent: _"I'm [active duty / Guard / Reserve] and I just received [PCS / deployment] orders. Walk me through my SCRA rights for my [lease / mortgage / pre-service credit card]."_[^ho4-2]

:::


::: fairness
The Fair Housing Act requires landlords and HOAs to allow reasonable modifications for people with disabilities --- grab bars, ramp access, wider doorways, lever handles, reserved accessible parking --- at the tenant's expense in rentals, at the association's expense in common areas. It also requires reasonable accommodations in rules and policies: a building with a no-pets policy must permit an assistance animal with documentation of disability-related need from a healthcare provider. Assistance animals under the FHA are not limited to dogs, do not require "certification" or "registration" from any website (those sites are scams, not legal requirements), and cannot be subject to breed, size, or weight restrictions. Landlords cannot charge pet deposits or pet rent for assistance animals. These are federal rights under [42 U.S.C. § 3604(f)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/42/3604). They are violated routinely. The National Fair Housing Alliance's annual trends report consistently finds that disability discrimination accounts for more than half of all fair housing complaints filed nationwide --- more than race, national origin, and every other protected class combined.[^ho4-3] If your landlord or HOA denies a modification or accommodation request, file with HUD (**1-800-669-9777**) or your [local fair housing organization](https://nationalfairhousing.org/find-help/). Ask your Agent: _"My landlord [or HOA] denied my request for [modification / assistance animal / policy exception]. Draft a response citing the specific Fair Housing Act provisions that apply in [my state]."_

:::


::: also
Housing financial assistance exists at every level --- federal, state, and local --- but no single office explains all of it. The largest program, HUD's Housing Choice Voucher program (Section 8), subsidizes rent for low-income families, but waitlists average 2.5 years and many are closed entirely; check your [local Public Housing Authority](https://www.hud.gov/program_offices/public_indian_housing/pha/contacts) for current status. For emergencies --- imminent eviction, homelessness, domestic violence --- call **211** or visit [211.org](https://www.211.org/) for local shelters, rapid rehousing, and emergency rental assistance. In rural areas, the [USDA Section 502 Direct Loan program](https://www.rd.usda.gov/programs-services/single-family-housing-programs/single-family-housing-direct-home-loans) offers subsidized mortgages with payments as low as 1% interest for very-low-income borrowers --- a program most people have never heard of. Ask your Agent: _"What housing assistance programs am I eligible for in [city, state] given my household income of [amount] and household size of [number]?"_

:::


::: tip
_"I'm concerned about [water quality / air quality / soil contamination / a nearby industrial facility] near my home in [city, state]. What should I test for, who do I report it to, and what are my rights as a [renter / homeowner]?"_ --- Your Agent can explain what contaminants to test for, identify your state environmental agency's complaint process, and help you understand your legal options. The [EPA's ECHO database](https://echo.epa.gov/) tracks facility compliance near you; for drinking water, your utility's annual [Consumer Confidence Report](https://www.epa.gov/ccr) is public and your Agent can decode it.

:::


*Common housing rights Expert Role specs:*

::: prompt
Act as a housing rights advisor. I live in [a community with
an HOA / a condo association] in [state].
The issue: [describe --- unreasonable rule, selective enforcement,
lack of financial transparency, special assessment, restricting
modifications (including solar panels or EV charging), not
maintaining common areas, or board overreach].
What are my rights under state law, what does the board's
fiduciary duty require, and what is the process for
challenging this?
Give me the most conservative, legally accurate answer.
I will verify with a tenant rights organization or attorney.

:::
::: prompt
Act as a property tax advisor. I own a home in [county, state]
and I believe my property tax assessment is [too high / based
on incorrect information about the property].
Current assessed value: [amount].
What I believe the correct value is, and why: [comparable sales,
property condition, errors in square footage or lot size,
historic district restrictions that limit use].
Walk me through the appeals process --- deadlines, evidence I need,
and whether to pursue an informal review or formal hearing.
Give me the most conservative, legally accurate answer.
I will verify with my county assessor's office or a tax professional.

:::

[^ho4-1]: Desmond, M. (2016). [_Evicted: Poverty and Profit in the American City._](https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/247816/evicted-by-matthew-desmond/) Crown. Hepburn, P., Louis, R., & Desmond, M. (2020). ["Racial and Gender Disparities among Evicted Americans."](https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.2116169119) _Sociological Science_, 7, 649--662. Eviction Lab (2025). ["Preliminary Analysis: Eviction Filing Patterns in 2024."](https://evictionlab.org/ets-report-2024/) Princeton University.

[^ho4-2]: Servicemembers Civil Relief Act, [50 U.S.C. §§ 3901--4043](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?path=/prelim@title50/chapter50&edition=prelim). U.S. Department of Justice, Servicemembers and Veterans Initiative, ["Financial and Housing Rights."](https://www.justice.gov/servicemembers/financial-and-housing-rights-0) Military OneSource, ["SCRA, The Servicemembers Civil Relief Act."](https://www.militaryonesource.mil/financial-legal/legal/servicemembers-civil-relief-act/) Rent-ceiling figure under 50 U.S.C. § 3951(a)(1)(A)(ii) from Department of Defense, ["Notice of Publication of Housing Price Inflation Adjustment,"](https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2025/05/20/2025-08911/notice-of-publication-of-housing-price-inflation-adjustment) 90 Fed. Reg. 21473 (May 20, 2025), effective Jan. 1, 2025.

[^ho4-3]: National Fair Housing Alliance. [_Fair Housing Trends Report._](https://nationalfairhousing.org/reports/) Published annually; disability consistently accounts for more than half of all fair housing complaints. HUD Office of Fair Housing and Equal Opportunity, ["Assistance Animals,"](https://www.hud.gov/program_offices/fair_housing_equal_opp/assistance_animals) including FHEO Notice 2020-01 on evaluating reasonable accommodation requests (January 2020). Fair Housing Act disability provisions: [42 U.S.C. § 3604(f)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/42/3604).

